@haydenadams I'm quite fascinated by what you just said. Do you mind sharing with me how it works? 

With the CLP design, 5 swaps of $10 will always pay less in fees than 1 swap of $50. Since at any point, a $10 swap has less "demand for liquidity" than a $50 swap, and the relationship isn't linear. The $10 swapper is more patient than the $50 swapper. However with a limited block space this now adds a time imperative into the decision-making process of a swapper. The adage "money always moves from the impatient to the patient" is true here. 

In the context that there is a lucrative arbitrage opportunity and that a swapper has factored in the profit margin (after the CLP fee the trade is still profitable), then the system will capture more in fees to liquidity providers.

